        "text": "The document page from the New York ISO Transmission and Dispatch Operations Manual outlines the \"Graduated Transmission Demand Curves\" and \"Locational Reserves.\"\n\n### Graduated Transmission Demand Curves\n- **NY Region**: Applies to all regions.\n- **Types**:\n  - **Facilities/Interfaces other than Identified Facilities with a non-zero CRM value**: \n    - Demand curves are segmented into six levels, each representing a percentage of the applicable CRM (Capacity Resource Margin) with corresponding prices ranging from $200 to $4,000 per MWh.\n  - **Identified Facilities**:\n    - Two levels: MW value equivalent to the applicable CRM ($100/MWh) and any MW value greater than the applicable CRM ($250/MWh).\n  - **Facilities/Interfaces with a zero CRM value**:\n    - Any MW value is priced at $4,000/MWh.\n\n### Locational Reserves\n- **Pricing and Requirements**: Determined by NYISO, with specific requirements for different areas including NYCA, Eastern New York, Southeastern New York, New York City, and Long Island.\n- **Scheduling**: Reserves are scheduled every five minutes and are co-optimized with energy and regulation schedules.\n- **Reserve Pickup**: During events, dispatchable suppliers are dispatched at the higher of their normal or emergency response rates. Notifications are sent to Transmission Operators (TOs) and resources via ICCP.\n- **30-minute Reserves**: Reserve Pickup will dispatch 30-minute Spinning Reserve.",
