        }
      },
      {
        "id": "dee11191-283c-4f88-90c1-8020f10d9388",
        "score": 0.58343697,
        "text": "The document page contains two figures illustrating real-time load-weighted generator congestion maps for 2022.\n\n1. **Figure A-58: NYCA Real-Time Load-Weighted Generator Congestion Map**\n   - This map shows congestion across New York Control Area (NYCA).\n   - Various locations are marked with circles of different sizes and colors, indicating congestion levels and prices.\n   - Key locations and their prices include:\n     - Iroquois Waddington: $7.17/MMBtu\n     - Millennium East: $5.61/MMBtu\n     - Iroquois Z2: $8.82/MMBtu\n     - Tennessee Z6: $9.20/MMBtu\n     - Transco Z6 NY: $7.04/MMBtu\n   - External regions like Ontario and PJM are also noted with prices of $37.22/MWh and $74.71/MWh, respectively.\n   - The color gradient from blue to red represents increasing congestion costs, ranging from $40 to $110.\n\n2. **Figure A-59: NYC Real-Time Load-Weighted Generator Congestion Map**\n   - This map focuses on congestion within New York City.\n   - It highlights transmission routes such as Transco and TETCO leading to NYC.\n   - Congestion costs are shown with a color gradient from $80 to $110.\n   - Specific areas like Iroquois (Hunts Point) are marked, indicating localized congestion.\n\nBoth maps provide a visual representation of congestion and associated costs in the NYCA and NYC areas for 2022.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2022/page_250.jpg",
          "page_num": 250,
          "title": "2022 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "2418dcc9-c47f-4f11-8e00-9e2963db9b4d",
        "score": 0.5829053,
        "text": "The document page discusses the uplift costs from guarantee payments in New York for the years 2016 and 2017. In 2017, the total uplift cost was $38 million, a 12% decrease from 2016's $43 million. The decline was mainly in Western New York, which saw a 49% reduction, and Long Island, with a 38% reduction. These reductions were due to less reliability commitment and out-of-market (OOM) dispatch. The local uplift in Western New York decreased significantly due to transmission upgrades and the expiration of the Milliken RSSA. The remaining local uplift could be eliminated if constraints were modeled in NYISO\u2019s day-ahead and real-time markets.\n\nAdditionally, the DAMAP, Min Oil Burn, and EDRP/SCR categories saw a reduction of over $5 million. Most uplift charges in 2016 occurred during high load days in July and August, which were not present in 2017 due to milder weather.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_109.jpg",
          "page_num": 109,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6bf9e6d7-30f9-4a1b-8501-e53131c3b173",
        "score": 0.58078456,
        "text": "The document page contains two figures related to transmission congestion in 2021.\n\n**Figure A-58: NYCA Real-Time Load-Weighted Generator Congestion Map**\n- This map shows congestion across New York Control Area (NYCA).\n- It highlights various locations with specific congestion prices in $/MMBtu and $/MWh.\n- Key points include:\n  - Iroquois Waddington: $3.77/MMBtu\n  - Millennium East: $3.03/MMBtu\n  - Iroquois Z2: $4.36/MMBtu\n  - Tennessee Z4 200L: $3.38/MMBtu\n  - Transco Z6 NY: $3.49/MMBtu\n  - Tennessee Z6: $4.68/MMBtu\n  - Ontario: $22.59/MWh\n  - PJM: $37.84/MWh\n  - ISO-NE: $43.03/MWh\n- The map uses a color gradient from $20 to $65 to indicate congestion levels.\n\n**Figure A-59: NYC Real-Time Load-Weighted Generator Congestion Map**\n- This map focuses on New York City.\n- It shows congestion prices ranging from $42 to $48.\n- Key locations include:\n  - Transco (to NYC)\n  - TETCO (to NYC)\n  - Iroquois (Hunts Point)\n- The map uses a color gradient from $42 to $48 to represent congestion levels.\n\nBoth maps use color-coded gradients to visually represent congestion levels, with specific locations marked and labeled with their respective congestion prices.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2021/page_228.jpg",
          "page_num": 228,
          "title": "2021 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "03e95aab-401b-4280-a2fc-f239dc7ba838",
        "score": 0.5727719,
        "text": "The document page presents two scenarios related to transmission congestion: the Basecase Scenario and the PAR Relief Scenario.\n\n### Basecase Scenario:\n- **Gen/Load Payments:**\n  - **Upstate:** LBMP $25, Load 10,000, Generation 13,000, Revenue $250,000, Generator Payments $325,000.\n  - **NYC:** LBMP $30, Load 4,000, Generation 1,900, Revenue $120,000, Generator Payments $57,000.\n  - **Valley Stream:** LBMP $50, Load 350, Generation 150, Revenue $17,500, Generator Payments $7,500.\n  - **Rest of Long Is.:** LBMP $35, Load 2,500, Generation 1,800, Revenue $87,500, Generator Payments $63,000.\n  - **Total:** Load 16,850, Generation 16,850, Revenue $475,000, Generator Payments $452,500.\n  - **Net (Gen minus Load):** $0, Congestion Revenue $22,500.\n\n- **Transmission Revenue:**\n  - **Interfaces:** Dunwoodie, Y50, 262 Line, 901 Line Contract.\n  - **Shadow Prices and Flows:** Dunwoodie $5 (2,000), Y50 $10 (1,000), 262 Line $15 (300), 901 Line Contract -$20 (100).\n  - **Congestion Revenue:** Total $22,500.\n\n### PAR Relief Scenario (901 Line Flow Reduced from 100 MW to 10 MW):\n- **Gen/Load Payments:**\n  - **Upstate:** Same as Basecase.\n  - **NYC:** LBMP $30, Load 4,000, Generation 1,990, Revenue $120,000, Generator Payments $59,700.\n  - **Valley Stream:** LBMP $50, Load 350, Generation 60, Revenue $17,500, Generator Payments $3,000.\n  - **Rest of Long Is.:** Same as Basecase.\n  - **Total:** Load 16,850, Generation 16,850, Revenue $475,000, Generator Payments $450,700.\n  - **Net (Gen minus Load):** $0, Congestion Revenue $24,300.\n\n- **Transmission Revenue:**\n  - **Interfaces:** Dunwoodie, Y50, 262 Line, 901 Line Contract, 901 Line Adjust.\n  - **Shadow Prices and Flows:** Dunwoodie $5 (2,000), Y50 $10 (1,000), 262 Line $15 (300), 901 Line Contract -$20 (100), 901 Line Adjust -$20 (-90).\n  - **Congestion Revenue:** Total $24,300.\n\nBoth scenarios analyze the load, generation, and financial aspects of different nodes, focusing on congestion revenue and transmission interface flows.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2018/page_235.jpg",
          "page_num": 235,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "47febeb0-b0a8-422a-bc00-f80872a715f1",
        "score": 0.5718268,
        "text": "The document evaluates the Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) at the primary PJM interface from 2016 to 2017. Key observations include:\n\n- **Improved Participation**: CTS participation at the PJM interface increased, with price-sensitive bids in the range of -$10 to $10/MWh rising from 30% in 2016 to 67% in 2017. The average bid quantity also increased from 82 MW to 245 MW.\n\n- **Comparison with NY/NE Interface**: Despite improvements, the average amount of price-sensitive bids at the PJM interface was lower than at the NY/NE interface. In 2017, 674 MW were offered at the NY/NE interface compared to 249 MW at the PJM interface. The NY/NE interface also cleared more price-sensitive bids.\n\n- **Differences in CTS Processes**: The differences are mainly due to large fees at the NY/PJM interface, while the NY/NE interface has no substantial charges. NYISO charges for exports to PJM range from $4 to $8/MWh, while PJM charges less than $2/MWh for imports and exports. These charges deter price-sensitive CTS bids at the NY/PJM border.\n\n- **Economic Barriers**: The fees at the NY/PJM interface create economic barriers, affecting efficient scheduling. At the ISO-NE border, most transactions were offered at less than $5/MWh, with profits under $1/MWh. At the PJM border, real-time export profits exceeded $8/MWh, with most day-ahead exports scheduled by participants with physical contracts, unaffected by export fees.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_240.jpg",
          "page_num": 240,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0ae21349-5a7a-4dce-b74d-9e981b8af7aa",
        "score": 0.5693692,
        "text": "The document page provides data on uplift costs from guarantee payments for the years 2016 and 2017, presented in two figures.\n\n1. **Figure A-84**: This figure shows uplift costs by month, categorized by local and statewide payments. The categories include Day Ahead, Real Time, DAMAP (Day-Ahead Margin Assurance Payment), and EDRP/SCR (Emergency Demand Response Program/Special Case Resources). The total uplift costs were $43 million in 2016 and $38 million in 2017.\n\n2. **Figure A-85**: This figure breaks down uplift costs by region, including New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, and Imports. The costs are further categorized by the same payment types as in Figure A-84. In 2016, the total was $43 million, while in 2017, it was $38 million.\n\nBoth figures highlight variations in costs across different months and regions, with detailed breakdowns of the specific categories contributing to the total uplift costs. The note clarifies that the figures are based on available information at the reporting time and may differ from final settlements due to manual adjustments.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_293.jpg",
          "page_num": 293,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "bd068fcd-7566-4af7-b95c-0786b9187fc9",
        "score": 0.5682237,
        "text": "The document page contains recommendations related to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) and its operations:\n\n1. **Efficient Pricing and Settlement for Congestion Relief (High Priority)**:\n   - NYISO should consider rules for efficient pricing and settlement when operating reserve providers help manage congestion.\n   - The current system does not compensate these providers adequately, leading to inefficient investment signals.\n   - The recommendation is crucial due to New York City's expected loss of up to 1300 MW of peaking generation over the next five years.\n   - Proper compensation for reserve providers is necessary to encourage investment in resources with flexible characteristics.\n\n2. **Eliminate Transaction Fees for CTS at the PJM-NYISO Border**:\n   - The Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) process with PJM has not met expectations since its implementation in 2014.\n   - Utilization of CTS at the ISO-NE interface is higher due to the absence of transaction fees.\n   - The recommendation suggests eliminating fees to improve the effectiveness of CTS with PJM, as current fees and uplift charges hinder its functionality.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_136.jpg",
          "page_num": 136,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3647f38a-b403-4232-8d35-aef1e3f5c8ea",
        "score": 0.56721437,
        "text": "The document contains two main recommendations:\n\n1. **Eliminate Transaction Fees for CTS at PJM-NYISO Border**: The Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) process with PJM has not met expectations since its implementation in 2014, partly due to high transaction fees. Eliminating these fees, as done between ISO-NE and NYISO, could increase profitability and utilization of CTS transactions. High fees have led to lower usage and increased costs for renewable generators exporting surplus power, impacting REC costs for ratepayers. The recommendation is to remove these fees to enhance efficiency and reduce costs.\n\n2. **Dynamically Adjust Operating Reserve Requirements**: The NYISO should modify its market software to optimize reserve procurement by considering unused import capability as reserves. This adjustment could reduce costs by using local resources more efficiently. The recommendation includes evaluating the need for longer lead-time reserve products, suggesting a 30-minute reserve requirement in market models to better represent these needs. This aims to improve the efficiency of reserve management and reduce unnecessary costs.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_162.jpg",
          "page_num": 162,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8d714b39-3512-4baa-8ca7-999d666c7516",
        "score": 0.5668472,
        "text": "The document discusses the evaluation of Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) at the primary PJM and NY/NE interfaces. Key observations include:\n\n- Despite improved participation in CTS at the PJM interface, the average amount of price-sensitive bids remains lower than at the NY/NE interface.\n- In 2018, 612 MW were offered at the NY/NE interface compared to 254 MW at the PJM interface.\n- Cleared price-sensitive bids at NY/NE nearly doubled those at PJM, indicating more active participation at NY/NE.\n- Interchange schedules were adjusted more frequently at NY/NE (77% of intervals) than at PJM (65%).\n- Projected production cost savings were higher at NY/NE ($6.3 million) than at PJM ($4.8 million).\n\nThe differences are attributed to large fees at the NY/PJM interface, while NY/NE has no substantial charges. NYISO charges exports to PJM at $6-$7/MWh, while PJM charges less than $2/MWh for imports/exports and less than $1/MWh for real-time deviations.\n\n- On the ISO-NE border, most transactions were offered at less than $5/MWh with a slight profit over $1/MWh.\n- On the PJM border, due to NYISO charges, no CTS export bids were offered at less than $5/MWh.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2018/page_253.jpg",
          "page_num": 253,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

