        "text": "The document page presents two scenarios related to transmission congestion: the Basecase Scenario and the PAR Relief Scenario.\n\n### Basecase Scenario:\n- **Gen/Load Payments:**\n  - **Upstate:** LBMP $25, Load 10,000, Generation 13,000, Revenue $250,000, Generator Payments $325,000.\n  - **NYC:** LBMP $30, Load 4,000, Generation 1,900, Revenue $120,000, Generator Payments $57,000.\n  - **Valley Stream:** LBMP $50, Load 350, Generation 150, Revenue $17,500, Generator Payments $7,500.\n  - **Rest of Long Is.:** LBMP $35, Load 2,500, Generation 1,800, Revenue $87,500, Generator Payments $63,000.\n  - **Total:** Load 16,850, Generation 16,850, Revenue $475,000, Generator Payments $452,500.\n  - **Net (Gen minus Load):** $0, Congestion Revenue $22,500.\n\n- **Transmission Revenue:**\n  - **Interfaces:** Dunwoodie, Y50, 262 Line, 901 Line Contract.\n  - **Shadow Prices and Flows:** Dunwoodie $5 (2,000), Y50 $10 (1,000), 262 Line $15 (300), 901 Line Contract -$20 (100).\n  - **Congestion Revenue:** Total $22,500.\n\n### PAR Relief Scenario (901 Line Flow Reduced from 100 MW to 10 MW):\n- **Gen/Load Payments:**\n  - **Upstate:** Same as Basecase.\n  - **NYC:** LBMP $30, Load 4,000, Generation 1,990, Revenue $120,000, Generator Payments $59,700.\n  - **Valley Stream:** LBMP $50, Load 350, Generation 60, Revenue $17,500, Generator Payments $3,000.\n  - **Rest of Long Is.:** Same as Basecase.\n  - **Total:** Load 16,850, Generation 16,850, Revenue $475,000, Generator Payments $450,700.\n  - **Net (Gen minus Load):** $0, Congestion Revenue $24,300.\n\n- **Transmission Revenue:**\n  - **Interfaces:** Dunwoodie, Y50, 262 Line, 901 Line Contract, 901 Line Adjust.\n  - **Shadow Prices and Flows:** Dunwoodie $5 (2,000), Y50 $10 (1,000), 262 Line $15 (300), 901 Line Contract -$20 (100), 901 Line Adjust -$20 (-90).\n  - **Congestion Revenue:** Total $24,300.\n\nBoth scenarios analyze the load, generation, and financial aspects of different nodes, focusing on congestion revenue and transmission interface flows.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2018/page_235.jpg",
          "page_num": 235,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "47febeb0-b0a8-422a-bc00-f80872a715f1",
        "score": 0.5718268,
        "text": "The document evaluates the Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) at the primary PJM interface from 2016 to 2017. Key observations include:\n\n- **Improved Participation**: CTS participation at the PJM interface increased, with price-sensitive bids in the range of -$10 to $10/MWh rising from 30% in 2016 to 67% in 2017. The average bid quantity also increased from 82 MW to 245 MW.\n\n- **Comparison with NY/NE Interface**: Despite improvements, the average amount of price-sensitive bids at the PJM interface was lower than at the NY/NE interface. In 2017, 674 MW were offered at the NY/NE interface compared to 249 MW at the PJM interface. The NY/NE interface also cleared more price-sensitive bids.\n\n- **Differences in CTS Processes**: The differences are mainly due to large fees at the NY/PJM interface, while the NY/NE interface has no substantial charges. NYISO charges for exports to PJM range from $4 to $8/MWh, while PJM charges less than $2/MWh for imports and exports. These charges deter price-sensitive CTS bids at the NY/PJM border.\n\n- **Economic Barriers**: The fees at the NY/PJM interface create economic barriers, affecting efficient scheduling. At the ISO-NE border, most transactions were offered at less than $5/MWh, with profits under $1/MWh. At the PJM border, real-time export profits exceeded $8/MWh, with most day-ahead exports scheduled by participants with physical contracts, unaffected by export fees.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_240.jpg",
          "page_num": 240,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0ae21349-5a7a-4dce-b74d-9e981b8af7aa",
        "score": 0.5693692,
        "text": "The document page provides data on uplift costs from guarantee payments for the years 2016 and 2017, presented in two figures.\n\n1. **Figure A-84**: This figure shows uplift costs by month, categorized by local and statewide payments. The categories include Day Ahead, Real Time, DAMAP (Day-Ahead Margin Assurance Payment), and EDRP/SCR (Emergency Demand Response Program/Special Case Resources). The total uplift costs were $43 million in 2016 and $38 million in 2017.\n\n2. **Figure A-85**: This figure breaks down uplift costs by region, including New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, and Imports. The costs are further categorized by the same payment types as in Figure A-84. In 2016, the total was $43 million, while in 2017, it was $38 million.\n\nBoth figures highlight variations in costs across different months and regions, with detailed breakdowns of the specific categories contributing to the total uplift costs. The note clarifies that the figures are based on available information at the reporting time and may differ from final settlements due to manual adjustments.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_293.jpg",
          "page_num": 293,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
